      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A circular buffer implementation failing to release memory when the index moves forward is a classic trap, almost always related to ownership or improper destruction. It's like a tiny, stubborn goblin who refuses to let go of a shiny pebble even after the designated spot has moved on.\n\nSince you're using a custom circular buffer, the failure almost certainly lies in the *destruction* phase, not the *indexing* phase. The index just tells you *where* the next slot is; it doesn't magically free the memory in the slot you just passed.\n\nHere are the most common ways this logic fails in C++ when dealing with raw pointers in a circular buffer:\n\n1.  **The Forgotten `delete` (The Most Likely Culprit):** When `remove_oldest()` executes, it retrieves the pointer at the head index. If you are using raw pointers (`DataLog*`), you *must* call `delete` on that pointer *before* you advance the head index. If you only advance the index and forget `delete log_store->head_ptr`, the memory block remains allocated, and your counter will climb, even though the buffer *thinks* it's clean.\n    *   *",
